					<p class="text-base leading-8 text-secondary">
						Texas child support orders can include medical support and dental support. A parent may be responsible for providing health insurance, paying dental insurance, reimbursing uninsured medical expenses, or contributing cash medical support depending on the order.
					</p>
					<p class="text-base leading-8 text-secondary">
						When the obligor pays child health or dental insurance, that amount may affect the net resources calculation or the final support discussion. The advanced options in this calculator let users enter child health insurance as a planning input, but actual orders may handle insurance responsibilities in more detail.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section id="irregular-income" class="grid scroll-mt-24 gap-5">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.04em] text-primary">Texas Child Support With Overtime, Bonuses, and Commissions</h2>
					<p class="text-base leading-8 text-secondary">
						Income is not always the same every month. Texas child support estimates may need to account for overtime, bonuses, commissions, self-employment income, or other variable income when those amounts are part of the income records used to estimate net resources.
					</p>
					<div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">
						<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
							<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">Does Overtime Count for Child Support in Texas?</h3>
							<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">Does overtime count for child support in Texas? It may, especially when overtime is regular enough to be part of the income picture. Texas child support overtime income can be more complicated when extra hours are seasonal, temporary, or unpredictable. A simple monthly calculator may not capture the full pattern. Parents may need to review several pay periods, annual earnings, or employer records before relying on an estimate. If overtime recently changed because of a new job, staffing shortage, or temporary project, that context may matter when discussing a planning estimate.</p>
						</article>
						<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
							<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">Do Bonuses Count for Child Support in Texas?</h3>
							<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">Do bonuses count for child support in Texas? They may be considered when calculating income used for support. Texas child support bonus income can vary widely, so the estimate may depend on whether bonuses are recurring, discretionary, or tied to a predictable compensation plan. A planning estimate should not assume every bonus is treated the same way. Documentation and income history can matter when deciding how to average bonus income. Parents may need to separate guaranteed compensation from one-time bonuses before deciding what monthly number to enter.</p>
						</article>
						<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
							<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">Do Commissions Count for Child Support in Texas?</h3>
							<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">Do commissions count for child support in Texas? Commission income may be included when estimating net resources. Texas child support commission income often requires more than one month of data because sales cycles, chargebacks, draws, and seasonal changes can affect take-home pay. If commissions are irregular, a court or professional may look at longer income history. Use the calculator for planning, then compare the result with reliable income records. Annual totals, recent pay statements, and employer documentation may all be useful when commissions change month to month.</p>
						</article>
					</div>
				</section>

